# Expression / query nesting-depth limit (CLAUDE.md §13; spec/design/cost.md §7). The SECOND
# untrusted-query safety gate (after the cost ceiling, cost_limit.test): a fixed maximum
# expression / subquery / set-operation NESTING DEPTH, checked in the parser, aborting with
# `54001` (statement_too_complex). It guards the NATIVE CALL STACK — a hazard the cost ceiling
# cannot catch, because deeply-nested input overflows the recursive-descent parser / resolve /
# eval walks BEFORE any cost is metered (such a statement would SIGABRT, or throw an
# uncatchable-by-design RangeError, even at max_cost = 1).
#
# The limit is a deterministic, cross-core-IDENTICAL constant (MAX_EXPR_DEPTH = 256) rather than
# PostgreSQL's runtime stack-pointer probe (build-/platform-dependent) — a documented divergence
# (CLAUDE.md §1/§8). So the SAME statement is accepted or rejected with 54001 in every core; this
# suite is the cross-core contract (it is jed-specific, so it is NOT oracle-checked). The
# over-limit statements below are nested 300 deep (> 256); each aborts at PARSE time, so no rows
# are produced and no cost is metered. Ordinary, modestly-nested SQL is unaffected.
# requires: ddl.create_table, ddl.primary_key, ddl.check, dml.insert, query.select, query.union, query.subquery_scalar, expr.arithmetic, types.array, types.int32, resource.depth_limit, resource.cost_metering


statement ok
CREATE TABLE t (id int32 PRIMARY KEY, v int32)

statement ok
INSERT INTO t VALUES (1, 1)

# A modestly-nested expression is well within the limit and evaluates normally — the gate
# does not perturb ordinary queries.
query I
SELECT ((((1 + 2) * 3) + 4)) FROM t
----
13

# An operator chain (`1 + 1 + ...`) nested past the limit aborts deterministically.
statement error 54001
